04906nam a22007095i 9781442682344DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161997onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002222452  a(OCoLC)1004875988  a(OCoLC)1011440163  a(OCoLC)1013956452  a(OCoLC)999360644  a97814426823447 a10.3138/97814426823442doi  a(DE-B1597)465034  a(OCoLC)944177327  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPHI0150002bisacsh04a128/.6/0922221 aRusson, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Self and its Body in Hegel's Phenomenology of Spirit /cJohn Russon. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Studies in Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Text -- tIntroduction: The Project of Reading Hegel’s Phenomenology of the Body -- tSection A: Self-Conscious Selfhood -- t1. Unhappy Consciousness and the Logic of Self-Conscious Selfhood -- t2. Reason and Dualism: The Category as the Immediacy of Unconditioned Self-Communion -- tSection B: Embodiment -- t3. The Condition of Self-Consciousness: The Body as the Phusis, Hexis, and Logos of the Self -- t4. The Zôion Politikon: The Body as the Institutions of Society -- tSection C: The Absolution of the Body -- t5. Responsibility and Science: The Body as Logos and Pathêtikos Nous -- tAppendix: Hegel’s Explicit Remarks on ‘Body’ -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major criticism of Hegel's philosophy is that it fails to comprehend the experience of the body. In this book, John Russon shows that there is in fact a philosophy of embodiment implicit in Hegel's Phenomenology of Spirit. Russon argues that Hegel has not only taken account of the body, but has done so in a way that integrates both modern work on embodiment and the approach to the body found in ancient Greek philosophy.Although Russon approaches Hegel's Phenomenology from a contemporary standpoint, he places both this standpoint and Hegel's work within a classical tradition. Using the Aristotelian terms of 'nature' and 'habit,' Russon refers to the classical distinction between biological nature and a cultural 'second nature.' It is this second nature that constitutes, in Russon's reading of Hegel, the true embodiment of human intersubjectivity. The development of spirit, as mapped out by Hegel, is interpreted here as a process by which the self establishes for itself an embodiment in a set of social and political institutions in which it can recognize and satisfy its rational needs. Russon concludes by arguing that self-expression and self-interpretation are the ultimate needs of the human spirit, and that it is the degree to which these needs are satisfied that is the ultimate measure of the adequacy of the institutions that embody human life.This link with classicism - in itself a serious contribution to the history of philosophy -provides an excellent point of access into the Hegelian system. Russon's work, which will prove interesting reading for any Hegel scholar, provides a solid and reliable introduction to the study of Hegel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268234440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682344.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA